(Yorkshire), or (least likely) Wortley in Wotton under Edge (Gloucestershire). The place in Tankersley derives from Old English <i>wyrt</i> ‘plant, vegetable’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’. The place in Armley derives from an Old English personal name <i>Wyrca</i> or <i>Weorca</i> + Old English <i>lēah</i>. The Gloucestershire placename derives from Old English <i>wyrt</i> + <i>lēah</i>."]},{"name":"Wherley","meanings":["English: possibly a variant of   Worley  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Warley","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more places so named, such as Great and Little Warley (Essex), Warley Salop and Warley Wigorn (Worcestershire), Warley (Yorkshire), Warleigh in Bathford (Somerset), and Warleigh House in Tamerton Foliot (Devon). The Essex and Somerset placenames derive from Old English <i>wer</i>, <i>wær</i> ‘weir’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. The Worcestershire placename may derive from a lost stream-name (of uncertain origin) or Old English <i>weorf</i> ‘cattle’ + <i>lēah</i>. The Yorkshire placename probably derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wērlāf</i> + Old English <i>lēah</i>. The Devon placename probably derives from Old English <i>weard</i> ‘watch’ + <i>lēah</i>. There may have been some confusion with   Worley   and   Whaley  ."]},{"name":"Whorley","meanings":["English (North Yorkshire and Durham): variant of   Worley  ."]},{"name":"Worlow","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Worley  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":29,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":60,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Worley was born in 1230, in Hipperholme, Yorkshire, England. She had at least 1 daughter with Henry de Rysshworth. She died in 1307, at the age of 77."},"et":{"1230–1307":"1230–1307","1225–1307":"1225–1307","1248–Female":"1248–Surnud","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1230":"1230","1307":"1307","1290":"1290","Hipperholme, Yorkshire, England":"Hipperholme, Yorkshire, England","Coley, Yorkshire, England":"Coley, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1230–1307":"1230–1307","1225–1307":"1225–1307","1248–Female":"1248–Kuollut","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1230":"1230","1307":"1307","1290":"1290","Hipperholme, Yorkshire, England":"Hipperholme, Yorkshire, England","Coley, Yorkshire, England":"Coley, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1230–1307":"1230–1307","1225–1307":"1225–1307","1248–Female":"1248–Décédée","1248":"1248","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1230":"1